# Assignment 3 - Building a Custom Visualization

You can run the code and interact with it. Click to set the lower limit of the range and then move the mouse with the long click to the upper limit of the desired range. This range tool is  used to evaluate the probability of a distributionâ€™s value  falling within a range. The probability that the distribution represented by the  error bar is contained in the region is mapped as a color to  the corresponding bar. 


```python
%matplotlib notebook
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib as mpl
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import math
from scipy import stats
from scipy.stats import norm
from scipy.stats import ttest_1samp
import matplotlib.gridspec as gridspec

# Function to adjust position in the y axis of graph

def position_yaxis(axs, howmuch, bot = None):
    h = None
    if bot == True:
        h = 3
    else: 
        h = 1
    exit_lst = [k for k in axs.get_position().bounds]
    exit_lst[h] = exit_lst[h] - howmuch
    return exit_lst

# Interactivity. You can click on the bar chart and move the mouse to another value and to set the range

def onclick(event):     
    global y1
    y1 = event.ydata
    principal.axhline(y1, color='gray', alpha=0.5, lw=0.5)
    principal.text(1991.45, y1-2000, '{0:.2f}'.format(y1))
    d1 = plt.gcf().canvas.mpl_connect('button_release_event', releaseclick)

def releaseclick(event): 
    principal.cla() 
    
    principal.axhline(event.ydata, color='gray', alpha=0.5, lw=0.5)
    principal.text(1991.45, event.ydata+500, '{0:.2f}'.format(event.ydata))
    
    principal.axhline(y1, color='gray', alpha=0.5, lw=0.5)
    principal.text(1991.45, y1-2000, '{0:.2f}'.format(y1))
    
    principal.axhspan(event.ydata, y1, color='gray', alpha=0.25)
    
    cm = []
    
    for i in range(1992,1996):
        _ , pval_sup = ttest_1samp(df.T[i], event.ydata)
        _ , pval_inf = ttest_1samp(df.T[i], y1)
        pval = np.abs(pval_inf - pval_sup)
        cm.append([v for k,v in df_colors.items() if pval > float(k[0]) and pval < float(k[1])][0])
        

    principal.bar(df.index,
                  df.mean(axis=1),
                  width=0.8,
                  tick_label=[k for k in range(1992, 1996)],
                  edgecolor = 'black',
                  yerr=df.sem(axis = 1) * norm.ppf(0.975),
                  capsize=10,
                  align='center',
                  color=cm)
    
    principal.set_title('Mean value Over a Dataset', fontsize=15, weight='bold')
    
    fig.canvas.mpl_disconnect(d1)             

# Data for this assignment

np.random.seed(12345)

df = pd.DataFrame([np.random.normal(32000,200000,3650), 
                   np.random.normal(43000,100000,3650), 
                   np.random.normal(43500,140000,3650), 
                   np.random.normal(48000,70000,3650)], 
                   index=[1992,1993,1994,1995])

df_colors = dict(zip([('{0:.2f}'.format(x*1/9), '{0:.2f}'.format(1/9 + 1/9*x)) for x in range(0, 9)], 
                     [mpl.colors.rgb2hex(mpl.cm.get_cmap('Pastel1') (i)) for i in range(mpl.cm.get_cmap('Pastel1').N)]))


# Create figure and "colorbar"

gspec = gridspec.GridSpec(9, 1)

principal = plt.subplot(gspec[0:-1, 0:])
color_b = plt.subplot(gspec[-1:, 0:])

# Initial conditions

principal.set_title('Mean value Over a Dataset', fontsize=15, weight='bold',  fontname='fantasy')

principal.bar(df.index,
              df.mean(axis=1),
              width=0.8,
              tick_label=[k for k in range(1992, 1996)],
              edgecolor = 'black',
              yerr=df.sem(axis = 1) * norm.ppf(0.975),
              capsize=10,
              align='center')

# "Colorbar"

col_map = plt.get_cmap('Pastel1')

cbar = mpl.colorbar.ColorbarBase(color_b,
                                 cmap=col_map,
                                 orientation = 'horizontal',
                                 ticks=[float('{0:.2f}'.format(x*1/9)) for x in range(0, 10)])

color_b.set_position(position_yaxis(color_b, 0.01))
color_b.set_position(position_yaxis(color_b, 0.05, bot = True))

# Set style to improve rendering

mpl.style.use(['seaborn-pastel', 'seaborn-ticks'])

# Connect the interactivity

plt.gcf().canvas.mpl_connect('button_press_event', onclick)

plt.show()
```
